Part 2- Visualization and Observations¶

In [114]:
#Plotting the GDP and Military Expenditure in the same bar graph for each year for each country

# This is to visualise the Military Expenditure relative to the GDP

i = 1
plt.figure(figsize=(32,30))

for rows in GDP1.index:
        
    plt.subplot(4,3,i)
    plt.bar(Year_List,GDP1.loc[rows])
    plt.bar(Year_List,ME1.loc[rows])
    plt.xlabel("Years")
    plt.ylabel("Billion USD")
    plt.legend(['GDP',"ME"],loc=2)
    plt.title(rows)
    i = i+1
    
    


plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    plt.plot(PERC_OF_ME1.loc[rows],marker = 'o')

plt.title('Comparison of Military Expenditue in Percentage of GDP', size = 'large')
plt.xlabel("Years",size = 'large')

plt.show()

It can be seen that Israel and Saudi Arabia have the highest percentage of military expenditure compared to its GDP (due to maybe the conflict in the Middle East) followed by United States and then Russia.¶

However Since the United States have a very high GDP, its absolute military expenditure will outshadow other countries. That fact isn't properly depicted by these bar plots and line graph¶

#Plotting a pie chart of the Military Expenditure of each year to show each countries' relative percentage compared to each other

    plt.legend(Country_List,loc=2,fontsize = 'xx-large')

    i = i+1
    j = j+1
    year = year+1
    

plt.show()

It can be seen that compared to other countries, China (Dark Blue) has the highest percentage increase in military spending throughout the years¶

Part 3- Predictions ¶

Countries' percentage Military Expenditure will stay at roughly the same level and its absolute value will only increase or decrease with the GDP.¶

If a conflict arises, then the percentage of military expenditure to GDP will increase to fund the battle. Likewise, if the Middle East conflict resolves, then the percentage of military expenditure to GDP of Saudi Arabia and Israel will decrease and the budget will be allocated else where.¶

Superpower like the United States will continue its high absolute military expenditure (even though the Military expenditure to GDP isn't significantly higher) to boast its military prowess across the globe unless significant reform occurs.¶

Finally, emerging superpower like China will also continue to increase its absolute and percentage of military expenditure in order to showcase their might too¶

Part 4- Conclusion¶

All in all, unless there is a conflict, countries will have around the same low percentage of military expenditure to GDP in the future. Also superpowers will have a relatively high absolute military expenditure in order to showcase its power.¶
